ther education (bad). D hot temper, know-it-all (maybe hinder). A not open to new ideas (bad). So all have issues.\n\nNow weigh: For long-distance flights, reliability, stress handling, decision-making, technical competence are crucial. Teamwork also important. B seems strong on stress handling, conscientiousness, weather assessment (critical). However, nasty remarks could affect crew morale. A has leadership but show-off and not open to new ideas, could affect crew. C is calm, quick decisions, but communication issues and unwillingness to learn. D is responsible, problem solving, but hot temper and know-it-all.\n\nThus B seems balanced: stress handling, conscientiousness, technical (weather, computers). Teamwork issue is nasty remarks, but maybe can be mitigated. D's hot temper may be more severe. C's communication issues may be severe for crew. A's lack of openness may hinder adaptation.\n\nThus provisional preference: Candidate B.\n\nWe should note uncertainties: we lack info on reliability of A, D, C beyond given; we lack info on teamwork for D (loner) but we have know-it-all, hot temper. We lack info on long-term development for B (memory for numbers). Also we lack info on actual leadership for B. So we can state that.\n\nNow produce public message summarizing evidence, mention that we have no extra info from others beyond what they said (they said they lack certain attributes). So we can note that.\n\nProceed."}
